worked_solutions.text:
At a given horizontal level in a static fluid with a free surface we know that the pressure must be constant. This means that the fluid under the piston must have a pressure equal to that beneath the raised height of mercury. We can write a force balance for the piston (including its weight, atmospheric pressure acting on its top surface, and the pressure under it), and for the raised column of mercury at the height of the piston's face.
         \(\begin{equation}
         mg + p_{atm}A_{piston} = pA_{piston}\hspace{0.5cm},\hspace{0.5cm}pA_{column} = (\rho g h + p_{atm})A_{column}
        \end{equation}\)
